('chunk_be3b522e1205c6fd9d','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Magnetizing, Demagnetizing & Induced Magnetism','**Definition.** A material can be *magnetized* by stroking it with a magnet in one direction, placing it in a strong field, or passing electric current through a coil around it. It can be *demagnetized* by heating, hammering, or applying an alternating current — all of which jumble the aligned domains. *Induced magnetism* is when a magnetic material becomes a temporary magnet while near a magnet.

**Real-world example.** A steel needle stroked with a magnet becomes a compass; dropping or heating a magnet weakens it.

**Analogy.** Magnetizing lines up tiny "compass" domains to point the same way; demagnetizing shakes them back into disorder, like tidying then scattering a row of pencils.

**Why it matters.** Explains how magnets are made, why they weaken, and how magnetic devices work.

**Misconception.** *"A magnet stays magnetic forever no matter what."* Wrong — heating, hammering or strong opposing fields can demagnetize it. Corrective: magnetism can be lost when domains are disrupted.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* one way to magnetize a steel bar. (recall)
2. *Describe* what happens to the domains when a magnet is heated strongly. (apply)
3. *Explain* how a paper clip becomes magnetic when held near a magnet (induced magnetism). (analyse)','{"magnetizing":2,"demagnetizing":2,"induced":3,"magnetism":4,"definition":1,"material":2,"can":4,"magnetized":1,"stroking":1,"with":2,"magnet":8,"one":2,"direction":1,"placing":1,"strong":2,"field":1,"passing":1,"electric":1,"current":2,"through":1,"coil":1,"around":1,"demagnetized":1,"heating":3,"hammering":2,"applying":1,"alternating":1,"all":1,"which":1,"jumble":1,"the":3,"aligned":1,"domains":4,"when":4,"magnetic":4,"becomes":3,"temporary":1,"while":1,"near":2,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"steel":2,"needle":1,"stroked":1,"compass":2,"dropping":1,"weakens":1,"analogy":1,"lines":1,"tiny":1,"point":1,"same":1,"way":2,"shakes":1,"them":1,"back":1,"into":1,"disorder":1,"like":1,"tidying":1,"then":1,"scattering":1,"row":1,"pencils":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"explains":1,"how":3,"magnets":1,"are":2,"made":1,"they":1,"weaken":1,"and":1,"devices":1,"work":1,"misconception":1,"stays":1,"forever":1,"matter":1,"what":2,"wrong":1,"opposing":1,"fields":1,"demagnetize":1,"corrective":1,"lost":1,"disrupted":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"state":1,"magnetize":1,"bar":1,"recall":1,"describe":1,"happens":1,"heated":1,"strongly":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"paper":1,"clip":1,"held":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_30cbfd6a41284cba04','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Soft Iron vs Steel; Permanent vs Electromagnets','**Definition.** *Soft magnetic materials* (soft iron) magnetize and demagnetize easily — good for temporary magnets. *Hard magnetic materials* (steel) are harder to magnetize but keep their magnetism — good for permanent magnets. A *permanent magnet* keeps its magnetism; an *electromagnet* is a coil of wire around a soft iron core that is magnetic only while current flows.

**Real-world example.** Electromagnets in scrapyard cranes lift cars and drop them by switching the current off; fridge magnets are permanent.

**Analogy.** Soft iron is like a light switch magnet — on when powered, off when not; steel is like a permanent tattoo of magnetism.

**Why it matters.** Choosing the right material and magnet type is key to motors, cranes, speakers, doorbells and data storage.

**Applications.** Electromagnets: cranes, electric bells, relays, MRI machines, electric motors. Permanent magnets: compasses, fridge magnets, loudspeakers, simple generators.

**Misconception.** *"An electromagnet stays magnetic after you switch off the current."* Wrong — a soft-iron-core electromagnet loses almost all magnetism when the current stops. Corrective: electromagnet magnetism depends on current flowing.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* one use of an electromagnet. (recall)
2. *Compare* the magnetic behaviour of soft iron and steel. (apply)
3. *Explain* why an electromagnet is more suitable than a permanent magnet for a scrapyard crane. (evaluate)

---','{"soft":7,"iron":6,"steel":4,"permanent":7,"electromagnets":3,"definition":1,"magnetic":5,"materials":2,"magnetize":2,"and":5,"demagnetize":1,"easily":1,"good":2,"for":3,"temporary":1,"magnets":5,"hard":1,"are":2,"harder":1,"but":1,"keep":1,"their":1,"magnetism":5,"magnet":4,"keeps":1,"its":1,"electromagnet":6,"coil":1,"wire":1,"around":1,"core":2,"that":1,"only":1,"while":1,"current":5,"flows":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"scrapyard":2,"cranes":3,"lift":1,"cars":1,"drop":1,"them":1,"switching":1,"the":5,"off":3,"fridge":2,"analogy":1,"like":2,"light":1,"switch":2,"when":3,"powered":1,"not":1,"tattoo":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"choosing":1,"right":1,"material":1,"type":1,"key":1,"motors":2,"speakers":1,"doorbells":1,"data":1,"storage":1,"applications":1,"electric":2,"bells":1,"relays":1,"mri":1,"machines":1,"compasses":1,"loudspeakers":1,"simple":1,"generators":1,"misconception":1,"stays":1,"after":1,"you":1,"wrong":1,"loses":1,"almost":1,"all":1,"stops":1,"corrective":1,"depends":1,"flowing":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"state":1,"one":1,"use":1,"recall":1,"compare":1,"behaviour":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"more":1,"suitable":1,"than":1,"crane":1,"evaluate":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_c6be0122d79163f36f','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Unit 3: Astrophysics','- **Key Concept:** Change
- **Related Concepts:** Models, Patterns, Development
- **Global Context:** Orientation in space and time — how we locate ourselves in the universe and understand its history.
- **Statement of Inquiry:** Scientific models of the universe develop and change as new evidence reveals patterns in the origin, structure and life cycle of celestial bodies.
- **Inquiry Questions:**
  - **Factual:** What is the Big Bang theory and what makes up the solar system?
  - **Conceptual:** How and why do scientific models of the universe change over time?
  - **Debatable:** Is the money spent on space research justified compared with needs on Earth?','{"unit":1,"astrophysics":1,"key":1,"concept":1,"change":3,"related":1,"concepts":1,"models":3,"patterns":2,"development":1,"global":1,"context":1,"orientation":1,"space":2,"and":6,"time":2,"how":2,"locate":1,"ourselves":1,"the":7,"universe":3,"understand":1,"its":1,"history":1,"statement":1,"inquiry":2,"scientific":2,"develop":1,"new":1,"evidence":1,"reveals":1,"origin":1,"structure":1,"life":1,"cycle":1,"celestial":1,"bodies":1,"questions":1,"factual":1,"what":2,"big":1,"bang":1,"theory":1,"makes":1,"solar":1,"system":1,"conceptual":1,"why":1,"over":1,"debatable":1,"money":1,"spent":1,"research":1,"justified":1,"compared":1,"with":1,"needs":1,"earth":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_a5b34047df55ad826c','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Big Bang Theory & Timeline','**Definition.** The Big Bang theory states that the universe began about 13.8 billion years ago from an extremely hot, dense point and has been expanding and cooling ever since. Introductory timeline: Big Bang → formation of the first atoms → first stars and galaxies → formation of the solar system → present day.

**Real-world example.** The observed *redshift* of distant galaxies (moving away from us) and the cosmic microwave background radiation are evidence the universe is expanding from a hot origin.

**Analogy.** The expanding universe is like dots on a balloon''s surface moving apart as the balloon inflates — every dot sees the others receding.

**Why it matters.** It is the leading scientific model of cosmic origins and a prime example of how models rest on evidence.

**Misconception.** *"The Big Bang was an explosion in empty space."* Wrong — space itself expanded; there was no pre-existing space for it to explode *into*. Corrective: the Big Bang is the expansion *of* space, not an explosion within it.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* approximately when the Big Bang occurred. (recall)
2. *Describe* one piece of evidence supporting the Big Bang theory. (apply)
3. *Explain* why galaxy redshift suggests an expanding universe. (analyse)','{"big":7,"bang":7,"theory":3,"timeline":2,"definition":1,"the":16,"states":1,"that":1,"universe":4,"began":1,"about":1,"billion":1,"years":1,"ago":1,"from":3,"extremely":1,"hot":2,"dense":1,"point":1,"and":5,"has":1,"been":1,"expanding":4,"cooling":1,"ever":1,"since":1,"introductory":1,"formation":2,"first":2,"atoms":1,"stars":1,"galaxies":2,"solar":1,"system":1,"present":1,"day":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":2,"observed":1,"redshift":2,"distant":1,"moving":2,"away":1,"cosmic":2,"microwave":1,"background":1,"radiation":1,"are":1,"evidence":3,"origin":1,"analogy":1,"like":1,"dots":1,"balloon":2,"surface":1,"apart":1,"inflates":1,"every":1,"dot":1,"sees":1,"others":1,"receding":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"leading":1,"scientific":1,"model":1,"origins":1,"prime":1,"how":1,"models":1,"rest":1,"misconception":1,"was":2,"explosion":2,"empty":1,"space":4,"wrong":1,"itself":1,"expanded":1,"there":1,"pre":1,"existing":1,"for":1,"explode":1,"into":1,"corrective":1,"expansion":1,"not":1,"within":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"state":1,"approximately":1,"when":1,"occurred":1,"recall":1,"describe":1,"one":1,"piece":1,"supporting":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"galaxy":1,"suggests":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_b8c2db71451e30e51e','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Heliocentric vs Geocentric Models','**Definition.** The *geocentric* model places Earth at the centre with everything orbiting it. The *heliocentric* model (Copernicus) places the Sun at the centre with planets, including Earth, orbiting it.

**Real-world example.** The apparent daily motion of the Sun across the sky once seemed to support geocentrism, but telescope observations (e.g. Galileo''s moons of Jupiter) supported heliocentrism.

**Analogy.** Geocentric thinking is like believing the scenery moves past a parked car; heliocentric is realising the car (Earth) is the one moving.

**Why it matters.** Shows how evidence overturns long-held models — a landmark in the history of science.

**Misconception.** *"The Sun orbits the Earth because it rises and sets."* Wrong — the Sun appears to move because Earth *rotates*. Corrective: Earth''s rotation, not the Sun''s motion, causes day and night.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* what is at the centre of the heliocentric model. (recall)
2. *Distinguish* between geocentric and heliocentric models. (apply)
3. *Explain* how new evidence led scientists to reject the geocentric model. (evaluate)','{"heliocentric":5,"geocentric":5,"models":3,"definition":1,"the":19,"model":4,"places":2,"earth":6,"centre":3,"with":2,"everything":1,"orbiting":2,"copernicus":1,"sun":5,"planets":1,"including":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"apparent":1,"daily":1,"motion":2,"across":1,"sky":1,"once":1,"seemed":1,"support":1,"geocentrism":1,"but":1,"telescope":1,"observations":1,"galileo":1,"moons":1,"jupiter":1,"supported":1,"heliocentrism":1,"analogy":1,"thinking":1,"like":1,"believing":1,"scenery":1,"moves":1,"past":1,"parked":1,"car":2,"realising":1,"one":1,"moving":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"shows":1,"how":2,"evidence":2,"overturns":1,"long":1,"held":1,"landmark":1,"history":1,"science":1,"misconception":1,"orbits":1,"because":2,"rises":1,"and":3,"sets":1,"wrong":1,"appears":1,"move":1,"rotates":1,"corrective":1,"rotation":1,"not":1,"causes":1,"day":1,"night":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"state":1,"what":1,"recall":1,"distinguish":1,"between":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"new":1,"led":1,"scientists":1,"reject":1,"evaluate":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_0a178a142a85d2d544','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','The Solar System: Planets & Asteroid Belt','**Definition.** The solar system is the Sun and everything bound to it by gravity: eight planets, their moons, and smaller bodies. In order from the Sun: Mercury, Venus, Earth, Mars, (asteroid belt), Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus, Neptune. The *asteroid belt* is a ring of rocky bodies between Mars and Jupiter.

**Real-world example.** The four inner planets are small and rocky; the four outer planets are large gas/ice giants — a pattern set by their formation.

**Analogy.** The Sun is like a campfire and the planets are people sitting at different distances — the closest feels the most heat.

**Why it matters.** Understanding our solar system frames Earth''s place and conditions for life.

**Misconception.** *"The asteroid belt is a densely packed field of rocks like in films."* Wrong — asteroids are spread over vast distances; spacecraft pass through easily. Corrective: the belt is mostly empty space with widely separated objects.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *List* the planets in order from the Sun. (recall)
2. *Identify* where the asteroid belt lies. (apply)
3. *Explain* why the inner and outer planets differ in size and composition. (analyse)','{"the":17,"solar":3,"system":3,"planets":7,"asteroid":5,"belt":6,"definition":1,"sun":4,"and":8,"everything":1,"bound":1,"gravity":1,"eight":1,"their":2,"moons":1,"smaller":1,"bodies":2,"order":2,"from":2,"mercury":1,"venus":1,"earth":2,"mars":2,"jupiter":2,"saturn":1,"uranus":1,"neptune":1,"ring":1,"rocky":2,"between":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"four":2,"inner":2,"are":4,"small":1,"outer":2,"large":1,"gas":1,"ice":1,"giants":1,"pattern":1,"set":1,"formation":1,"analogy":1,"like":2,"campfire":1,"people":1,"sitting":1,"different":1,"distances":2,"closest":1,"feels":1,"most":1,"heat":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"understanding":1,"our":1,"frames":1,"place":1,"conditions":1,"for":1,"life":1,"misconception":1,"densely":1,"packed":1,"field":1,"rocks":1,"films":1,"wrong":1,"asteroids":1,"spread":1,"over":1,"vast":1,"spacecraft":1,"pass":1,"through":1,"easily":1,"corrective":1,"mostly":1,"empty":1,"space":1,"with":1,"widely":1,"separated":1,"objects":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"list":1,"recall":1,"identify":1,"where":1,"lies":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"differ":1,"size":1,"composition":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_c6cf2829ea19b7ed73','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Galaxies — Types','**Definition.** A galaxy is a huge system of stars, gas, dust and dark matter held together by gravity. Main types: *spiral* (arms winding out, like the Milky Way), *elliptical* (rounded/oval, older stars), and *irregular* (no clear shape).

**Real-world example.** We live in the Milky Way, a spiral galaxy of over 100 billion stars.

**Analogy.** Galaxy types are like city layouts — spirals with orderly avenues, ellipticals a rounded blob, irregulars a sprawling unplanned town.

**Why it matters.** Galaxy types reveal how star systems form and evolve over cosmic time.

**Misconception.** *"The Milky Way is the whole universe."* Wrong — there are billions of galaxies beyond ours. Corrective: the Milky Way is just one galaxy among an estimated two trillion.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *Name* the galaxy we live in. (recall)
2. *Classify* a galaxy with winding arms. (apply)
3. *Explain* how astronomers might use a galaxy''s shape to infer its age. (analyse)','{"100":1,"galaxies":2,"types":4,"definition":1,"galaxy":8,"huge":1,"system":1,"stars":3,"gas":1,"dust":1,"and":3,"dark":1,"matter":1,"held":1,"together":1,"gravity":1,"main":1,"spiral":2,"arms":2,"winding":2,"out":1,"like":2,"the":6,"milky":4,"way":4,"elliptical":1,"rounded":2,"oval":1,"older":1,"irregular":1,"clear":1,"shape":2,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"live":2,"over":2,"billion":1,"analogy":1,"are":2,"city":1,"layouts":1,"spirals":1,"with":2,"orderly":1,"avenues":1,"ellipticals":1,"blob":1,"irregulars":1,"sprawling":1,"unplanned":1,"town":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"reveal":1,"how":2,"star":1,"systems":1,"form":1,"evolve":1,"cosmic":1,"time":1,"misconception":1,"whole":1,"universe":1,"wrong":1,"there":1,"billions":1,"beyond":1,"ours":1,"corrective":1,"just":1,"one":1,"among":1,"estimated":1,"two":1,"trillion":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"name":1,"recall":1,"classify":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"astronomers":1,"might":1,"use":1,"infer":1,"its":1,"age":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_a958b0cf5d4cbfc99d','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Eclipses','**Definition.** An eclipse occurs when one body''s shadow falls on another. A *solar eclipse* happens when the Moon passes between the Sun and Earth, blocking sunlight. A *lunar eclipse* happens when Earth passes between the Sun and Moon, casting Earth''s shadow on the Moon.

**Real-world example.** During a total solar eclipse, day briefly turns to twilight along a narrow path on Earth.

**Analogy.** A solar eclipse is like someone holding a coin close to your eye to block a distant lamp; a lunar eclipse is the coin (Moon) falling into a bigger shadow.

**Why it matters.** Eclipses demonstrate the geometry and motion of the Sun-Earth-Moon system.

**Described diagram.** Solar eclipse: Sun — Moon — Earth in a line, Moon''s shadow hitting Earth. Lunar eclipse: Sun — Earth — Moon in a line, Earth''s shadow hitting the Moon.

**Misconception.** *"Eclipses happen every month at full and new moon."* Wrong — the Moon''s orbit is tilted, so alignment is exact only occasionally. Corrective: eclipses need the three bodies to line up precisely, which is rare.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* what lies between the Sun and Earth during a solar eclipse. (recall)
2. *Describe* the arrangement of bodies during a lunar eclipse. (apply)
3. *Explain* why eclipses do not occur every month. (analyse)','{"eclipses":5,"definition":1,"eclipse":10,"occurs":1,"when":3,"one":1,"body":1,"shadow":5,"falls":1,"another":1,"solar":5,"happens":2,"the":12,"moon":11,"passes":2,"between":3,"sun":6,"and":5,"earth":10,"blocking":1,"sunlight":1,"lunar":4,"casting":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"during":3,"total":1,"day":1,"briefly":1,"turns":1,"twilight":1,"along":1,"narrow":1,"path":1,"analogy":1,"like":1,"someone":1,"holding":1,"coin":2,"close":1,"your":1,"eye":1,"block":1,"distant":1,"lamp":1,"falling":1,"into":1,"bigger":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"demonstrate":1,"geometry":1,"motion":1,"system":1,"described":1,"diagram":1,"line":3,"hitting":2,"misconception":1,"happen":1,"every":2,"month":2,"full":1,"new":1,"wrong":1,"orbit":1,"tilted":1,"alignment":1,"exact":1,"only":1,"occasionally":1,"corrective":1,"need":1,"three":1,"bodies":2,"precisely":1,"which":1,"rare":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"state":1,"what":1,"lies":1,"recall":1,"describe":1,"arrangement":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"not":1,"occur":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_5ba2b224ae5fdf73e8','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Life Cycle of a Star','**Definition.** A star forms from a collapsing cloud of gas and dust (nebula), shines steadily during its *main sequence* while fusing hydrogen, then swells into a red giant. Low-mass stars end as a white dwarf; massive stars explode as a supernova, leaving a neutron star or black hole.

**Real-world example.** Our Sun is a middle-aged main-sequence star that will become a red giant, then a white dwarf, in billions of years.

**Analogy.** A star''s life is like a human''s — born, long adult life, then old age and death — but scaled to billions of years.

**Why it matters.** Star life cycles explain where chemical elements (including those in our bodies) come from.

**Described diagram.** A flow: Nebula → Protostar → Main-sequence star → Red giant → (low mass) White dwarf, or (high mass) Supernova → Neutron star / Black hole.

**Misconception.** *"Stars live forever."* Wrong — stars have finite fuel and eventually die. Corrective: every star has a life cycle ending when its fuel runs out.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* what a star forms from. (recall)
2. *Describe* the stages in the life cycle of a low-mass star like the Sun. (apply)
3. *Explain* why a massive star ends differently from a low-mass star. (analyse)','{"life":6,"cycle":3,"star":13,"definition":1,"forms":2,"from":4,"collapsing":1,"cloud":1,"gas":1,"and":3,"dust":1,"nebula":2,"shines":1,"steadily":1,"during":1,"its":2,"main":3,"sequence":3,"while":1,"fusing":1,"hydrogen":1,"then":3,"swells":1,"into":1,"red":3,"giant":3,"low":4,"mass":5,"stars":4,"end":1,"white":3,"dwarf":3,"massive":2,"explode":1,"supernova":2,"leaving":1,"neutron":2,"black":2,"hole":2,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"our":2,"sun":2,"middle":1,"aged":1,"that":1,"will":1,"become":1,"billions":2,"years":2,"analogy":1,"like":2,"human":1,"born":1,"long":1,"adult":1,"old":1,"age":1,"death":1,"but":1,"scaled":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"cycles":1,"explain":2,"where":1,"chemical":1,"elements":1,"including":1,"those":1,"bodies":1,"come":1,"described":1,"diagram":1,"flow":1,"protostar":1,"high":1,"misconception":1,"live":1,"forever":1,"wrong":1,"have":1,"finite":1,"fuel":2,"eventually":1,"die":1,"corrective":1,"every":1,"has":1,"ending":1,"when":1,"runs":1,"out":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"state":1,"what":1,"recall":1,"describe":1,"the":3,"stages":1,"apply":1,"ends":1,"differently":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_87e461edfc9d9840ab','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Celestial Bodies: Comets, Asteroids, Meteors, Meteorites','**Definition.**
- *Comet:* icy body that grows a glowing tail of gas and dust when near the Sun.
- *Asteroid:* rocky body, mostly in the asteroid belt.
- *Meteoroid:* small rock/debris in space.
- *Meteor:* a meteoroid burning up in Earth''s atmosphere — a "shooting star."
- *Meteorite:* a meteor that survives and lands on Earth''s surface.

**Real-world example.** Halley''s Comet returns about every 76 years; meteor showers occur when Earth passes through comet debris.

**Analogy.** A meteoroid is a stone in space, a meteor is that stone glowing as it "skids" through the air, and a meteorite is the stone that hits the ground.

**Why it matters.** These bodies carry clues about the solar system''s formation and pose occasional impact hazards.

**Misconception.** *"A shooting star is a real star falling."* Wrong — it is a small rock burning up in the atmosphere. Corrective: meteors are tiny debris, not stars.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *Define* a meteorite. (recall)
2. *Distinguish* between a meteor and a meteorite. (apply)
3. *Explain* why a comet develops a tail as it nears the Sun. (analyse)','{"celestial":1,"bodies":2,"comets":1,"asteroids":1,"meteors":2,"meteorites":1,"definition":1,"comet":4,"icy":1,"body":2,"that":4,"grows":1,"glowing":2,"tail":2,"gas":1,"and":5,"dust":1,"when":2,"near":1,"the":8,"sun":2,"asteroid":2,"rocky":1,"mostly":1,"belt":1,"meteoroid":3,"small":2,"rock":2,"debris":3,"space":2,"meteor":5,"burning":2,"earth":3,"atmosphere":2,"shooting":2,"star":3,"meteorite":4,"survives":1,"lands":1,"surface":1,"real":2,"world":1,"example":1,"halley":1,"returns":1,"about":2,"every":1,"years":1,"showers":1,"occur":1,"passes":1,"through":2,"analogy":1,"stone":3,"skids":1,"air":1,"hits":1,"ground":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"these":1,"carry":1,"clues":1,"solar":1,"system":1,"formation":1,"pose":1,"occasional":1,"impact":1,"hazards":1,"misconception":1,"falling":1,"wrong":1,"corrective":1,"are":1,"tiny":1,"not":1,"stars":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"define":1,"recall":1,"distinguish":1,"between":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"develops":1,"nears":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_75e183450b9b43c985','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Satellites & Types','**Definition.** A satellite is any object that orbits a larger body. *Natural satellites* are moons; *artificial satellites* are human-made and include communication, weather, GPS/navigation, and scientific/observation satellites.

**Real-world example.** The Moon is Earth''s natural satellite; GPS satellites let phones pinpoint location.

**Analogy.** A satellite orbiting is like a ball whirled on a string — gravity is the "string" keeping it circling.

**Why it matters.** Satellites underpin modern communication, navigation, weather forecasting and Earth monitoring.

**Misconception.** *"Satellites stay up because there is no gravity in space."* Wrong — gravity is what holds them in orbit; they are constantly falling *around* Earth. Corrective: orbit is continuous free-fall balanced by forward speed, not the absence of gravity.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* what a natural satellite is. (recall)
2. *List* two uses of artificial satellites. (apply)
