('chunk_846ab2c6e106bb707e','file_14c714e4dfcb7d1697','theatre.md','Concept: What Theatre *Is*','**Definition.** Theatre is a **live performing art** in which performers (actors) present a story or idea to an **audience**, usually in a shared space and time. The word comes from the Greek *theatron* — "a place for seeing." Its defining feature is **liveness**: performer and audience are present together, and the event happens now.

**Real example.** A class staging a short scene from Sophocles'' *Antigone*; a touring production of the musical *The Lion King*; a street mime performing in a park.

**Analogy.** A film is like a painting you view later; theatre is like a conversation — it only fully exists while both sides are in the room together.

**Why it matters.** Understanding theatre as *live communication* explains every other idea in the unit: why the audience matters, why a "mistake" is handled differently on stage than on film, and why the same script feels different every night.

**Common misconception.** *"Theatre is just actors memorising and reciting lines."*
**Correction.** Lines are only one layer. Theatre also depends on movement, voice, timing, space, design, and — crucially — a live relationship with the audience. Acting is *reacting* and *doing*, not reciting.

**Command-term questions.**
- *Identify* two features that make theatre "live."
- *Describe* the purpose of theatre in your own words.
- *Analyse* how being "live" changes the relationship between actor and audience.

---','{"concept":1,"what":1,"theatre":8,"definition":1,"live":5,"performing":2,"art":1,"which":1,"performers":1,"actors":2,"present":2,"story":1,"idea":2,"audience":5,"usually":1,"shared":1,"space":2,"and":8,"time":1,"the":12,"word":1,"comes":1,"from":2,"greek":1,"theatron":1,"place":1,"for":1,"seeing":1,"its":1,"defining":1,"feature":1,"liveness":1,"performer":1,"are":3,"together":2,"event":1,"happens":1,"now":1,"real":1,"example":1,"class":1,"staging":1,"short":1,"scene":1,"sophocles":1,"antigone":1,"touring":1,"production":1,"musical":1,"lion":1,"king":1,"street":1,"mime":1,"park":1,"analogy":1,"film":2,"like":2,"painting":1,"you":1,"view":1,"later":1,"conversation":1,"only":2,"fully":1,"exists":1,"while":1,"both":1,"sides":1,"room":1,"why":4,"matters":2,"understanding":1,"communication":1,"explains":1,"every":2,"other":1,"unit":1,"mistake":1,"handled":1,"differently":1,"stage":1,"than":1,"same":1,"script":1,"feels":1,"different":1,"night":1,"common":1,"misconception":1,"just":1,"memorising":1,"reciting":2,"lines":2,"correction":1,"one":1,"layer":1,"also":1,"depends":1,"movement":1,"voice":1,"timing":1,"design":1,"crucially":1,"relationship":2,"with":1,"acting":1,"reacting":1,"doing":1,"not":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"identify":1,"two":1,"features":1,"that":1,"make":1,"describe":1,"purpose":1,"your":1,"own":1,"words":1,"analyse":1,"how":1,"being":1,"changes":1,"between":1,"actor":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_4e099bd9e4e02928be','file_14c714e4dfcb7d1697','theatre.md','Concept: The Purpose of Theatre','**Definition.** Theatre exists to **entertain, move, teach, question, celebrate, and bring people together**. Across history it has served ritual and religious purposes (Greek festivals of Dionysus), civic and political debate, storytelling, and pure entertainment.

**Real example.** Greek tragedy explored justice and fate; Roman comedy entertained huge crowds; modern "Theatre in Education" teaches audiences about real issues.

**Why it matters.** Knowing *why* a piece was made helps us judge whether it succeeds (Criterion D — Evaluating).

**Common misconception.** *"Theatre is only for entertainment."*
**Correction.** Entertainment is one purpose among many — theatre can protest, mourn, worship, or educate.

**Command-term questions.**
- *Identify* three different purposes theatre can serve.
- *Interpret* what a playwright might want an audience to feel or think.

---','{"concept":1,"the":1,"purpose":2,"theatre":6,"definition":1,"exists":1,"entertain":1,"move":1,"teach":1,"question":1,"celebrate":1,"and":5,"bring":1,"people":1,"together":1,"across":1,"history":1,"has":1,"served":1,"ritual":1,"religious":1,"purposes":2,"greek":2,"festivals":1,"dionysus":1,"civic":1,"political":1,"debate":1,"storytelling":1,"pure":1,"entertainment":3,"real":2,"example":1,"tragedy":1,"explored":1,"justice":1,"fate":1,"roman":1,"comedy":1,"entertained":1,"huge":1,"crowds":1,"modern":1,"education":1,"teaches":1,"audiences":1,"about":1,"issues":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"knowing":1,"piece":1,"was":1,"made":1,"helps":1,"judge":1,"whether":1,"succeeds":1,"criterion":1,"evaluating":1,"common":1,"misconception":1,"only":1,"for":1,"correction":1,"one":1,"among":1,"many":1,"can":2,"protest":1,"mourn":1,"worship":1,"educate":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"identify":1,"three":1,"different":1,"serve":1,"interpret":1,"what":1,"playwright":1,"might":1,"want":1,"audience":1,"feel":1,"think":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_62e692f1f96e37d2db','file_14c714e4dfcb7d1697','theatre.md','Concept: Essential Theatre Vocabulary','**Definition & importance.** A shared vocabulary lets performers, directors, and designers communicate quickly and precisely. Using correct terms is directly assessed under **Criterion A (Investigating / Knowing & understanding)**.

**Stage geography.** Stage directions are given **from the actor''s point of view as they face the audience** — this is the single most common source of confusion.

| Term | Meaning |
|------|---------|
| **Stage** | The area where the performance happens. |
| **Upstage** | The part of the stage **furthest from the audience** (historically raked/higher). |
| **Downstage** | The part **closest to the audience**. |
| **Stage left / Stage right** | Left/right **from the actor''s perspective** (so stage right is the audience''s left). |
| **Centre stage** | The middle of the acting area. |
| **Wings** | The offstage areas at the sides, hidden from the audience, where actors wait to enter. |
| **Backstage** | Everything behind/around the stage the audience cannot see. |

**Key people and text terms.**

| Term | Meaning | Example |
|------|---------|---------|
| **Audience** | The people watching the performance. | The spectators in an amphitheatre. |
| **Dialogue** | Spoken exchange **between two or more characters**. | Two characters arguing in a scene. |
| **Monologue** | A **long speech by one character** to others or the audience. | A character revealing their plan aloud. |
| **Script** | The written text: dialogue plus stage directions. | The playscript of *Antigone*. |
| **Cast** | The group of actors performing the roles. | "The cast took a bow." |
| **Director** | The person who guides the artistic vision and shapes the performance. | Decides how a scene is staged. |
| **Props** | *Properties* — movable objects actors handle. | A sword, a letter, a cup. |
| **Set** | The constructed scenery showing the location. | A painted palace backdrop. |
| **Costume** | What the performers wear to show character/period. | A king''s robe. |
| **Cue** | A signal (line, sound, or action) to do something next. | An actor''s exit cue; a lighting cue. |
| **Blocking** | The planned movement and positioning of actors on stage. | "Cross downstage on that line." |

**Analogy for blocking.** Blocking is like choreography for a scene — a map of who moves where and when, so the stage picture stays clear.

**Analogy for a cue.** A cue is a relay-race baton: the moment you receive it, it''s your turn to act.

**Common misconception.** *"Stage left is on my left as I sit in the audience."*
**Correction.** Stage left/right are always from the **actor''s** viewpoint facing the audience — the opposite of the audience''s left/right.

**Command-term questions.**
- *Identify* the difference between a monologue and dialogue.
- *Describe* where the "wings" are and what they are used for.
- *Apply* correct stage directions to move an actor from upstage-right to downstage-centre.

---','{"concept":1,"essential":1,"theatre":1,"vocabulary":2,"definition":1,"importance":1,"shared":1,"lets":1,"performers":2,"directors":1,"and":8,"designers":1,"communicate":1,"quickly":1,"precisely":1,"using":1,"correct":2,"terms":2,"directly":1,"assessed":1,"under":1,"criterion":1,"investigating":1,"knowing":1,"understanding":1,"stage":15,"geography":1,"directions":3,"are":4,"given":1,"from":6,"the":44,"actor":5,"point":1,"view":1,"they":2,"face":1,"audience":11,"this":1,"single":1,"most":1,"common":2,"source":1,"confusion":1,"term":3,"meaning":2,"area":2,"where":4,"performance":3,"happens":1,"upstage":2,"part":2,"furthest":1,"historically":1,"raked":1,"higher":1,"downstage":3,"closest":1,"left":7,"right":6,"perspective":1,"centre":2,"middle":1,"acting":1,"wings":2,"offstage":1,"areas":1,"sides":1,"hidden":1,"actors":4,"wait":1,"enter":1,"backstage":1,"everything":1,"behind":1,"around":1,"cannot":1,"see":1,"key":1,"people":2,"text":2,"example":1,"watching":1,"spectators":1,"amphitheatre":1,"dialogue":3,"spoken":1,"exchange":1,"between":2,"two":2,"more":1,"characters":2,"arguing":1,"scene":3,"monologue":2,"long":1,"speech":1,"one":1,"character":3,"others":1,"revealing":1,"their":1,"plan":1,"aloud":1,"script":1,"written":1,"plus":1,"playscript":1,"antigone":1,"cast":2,"group":1,"performing":1,"roles":1,"took":1,"bow":1,"director":1,"person":1,"who":2,"guides":1,"artistic":1,"vision":1,"shapes":1,"decides":1,"how":1,"staged":1,"props":1,"properties":1,"movable":1,"objects":1,"handle":1,"sword":1,"letter":1,"cup":1,"set":1,"constructed":1,"scenery":1,"showing":1,"location":1,"painted":1,"palace":1,"backdrop":1,"costume":1,"what":2,"wear":1,"show":1,"period":1,"king":1,"robe":1,"cue":5,"signal":1,"line":2,"sound":1,"action":1,"something":1,"next":1,"exit":1,"lighting":1,"blocking":3,"planned":1,"movement":1,"positioning":1,"cross":1,"that":1,"analogy":2,"for":4,"like":1,"choreography":1,"map":1,"moves":1,"when":1,"picture":1,"stays":1,"clear":1,"relay":1,"race":1,"baton":1,"moment":1,"you":1,"receive":1,"your":1,"turn":1,"act":1,"misconception":1,"sit":1,"correction":1,"always":1,"viewpoint":1,"facing":1,"opposite":1,"command":1,"questions":1,"identify":1,"difference":1,"describe":1,"used":1,"apply":1,"move":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_7375261d6c87f2897f','file_14c714e4dfcb7d1697','theatre.md','Concept: Kinds (Forms) of Performance','**Definition.** Theatre takes many **forms**, each with its own conventions.

| Form | What it is | Example |
|------|-----------|---------|
| **Play (spoken drama)** | A story told mainly through dialogue and action. | *Antigone*; a modern stage play. |
| **Musical** | Story told through song, dialogue, and dance. | *The Lion King*, *Matilda the Musical*. |
| **Mime** | Storytelling through movement and gesture, **no speech**. | A mime "trapped in a box." |
| **Puppetry** | Objects/puppets are animated to perform. | Shadow puppetry; *War Horse* puppets. |
| **Improvisation (improv)** | Performance created spontaneously, unscripted. | A "make-up-a-scene" game. |
| **Physical theatre** | Meaning made mainly through the body and movement. | Ensemble movement pieces. |
| **Comedy / Tragedy** | Genres by tone and outcome (see Unit 1c). | Aristophanes'' comedies; Greek tragedies. |

**Why it matters.** Recognising forms lets students choose the right conventions for their own devised work (Criteria B and C).

**Common misconception.** *"Mime and improv are just messing about / warm-up games."*
**Correction.** Both are disciplined forms with real techniques — mime demands precise, controlled gesture; improv relies on skills like "accepting offers" (saying "yes, and…") and listening.

**Command-term questions.**
- *Identify* three forms of theatre that do not rely on spoken dialogue.
- *Describe* one convention of musical theatre.
- *Evaluate* which form would best suit a story with no words.

---','{"concept":1,"kinds":1,"forms":5,"performance":2,"definition":1,"theatre":4,"takes":1,"many":1,"each":1,"with":3,"its":1,"own":2,"conventions":2,"form":2,"what":1,"example":1,"play":2,"spoken":2,"drama":1,"story":3,"told":2,"mainly":2,"through":4,"dialogue":3,"and":9,"action":1,"antigone":1,"modern":1,"stage":1,"musical":3,"song":1,"dance":1,"the":4,"lion":1,"king":1,"matilda":1,"mime":4,"storytelling":1,"movement":3,"gesture":2,"speech":1,"trapped":1,"box":1,"puppetry":2,"objects":1,"puppets":2,"are":3,"animated":1,"perform":1,"shadow":1,"war":1,"horse":1,"improvisation":1,"improv":3,"created":1,"spontaneously":1,"unscripted":1,"make":1,"scene":1,"game":1,"physical":1,"meaning":1,"made":1,"body":1,"ensemble":1,"pieces":1,"comedy":1,"tragedy":1,"genres":1,"tone":1,"outcome":1,"see":1,"unit":1,"aristophanes":1,"comedies":1,"greek":1,"tragedies":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"recognising":1,"lets":1,"students":1,"choose":1,"right":1,"for":1,"their":1,"devised":1,"work":1,"criteria":1,"common":1,"misconception":1,"just":1,"messing":1,"about":1,"warm":1,"games":1,"correction":1,"both":1,"disciplined":1,"real":1,"techniques":1,"demands":1,"precise":1,"controlled":1,"relies":1,"skills":1,"like":1,"accepting":1,"offers":1,"saying":1,"yes":1,"listening":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"identify":1,"three":1,"that":1,"not":1,"rely":1,"describe":1,"one":1,"convention":1,"evaluate":1,"which":1,"would":1,"best":1,"suit":1,"words":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_96afe50ce30d176f28','file_14c714e4dfcb7d1697','theatre.md','Concept: The Elements of Drama (Overview)','**Definition.** The elements of drama are the **building blocks** every piece of theatre combines. Grade 7 focuses on the core three — **plot, character, theme** — and connects them to the classic Aristotelian set.

**Aristotle''s six elements** (from *Poetics*, ~335 BCE) — age-appropriate awareness level:

| Aristotle''s element | Simple meaning |
|---------------------|----------------|
| **Plot (mythos)** | The arrangement of events — the story''s structure. |
| **Character (ethos)** | The people in the story and their qualities. |
| **Theme / Thought (dianoia)** | The ideas and meanings explored. |
| **Diction / Language (lexis)** | The words spoken — dialogue and how it''s expressed. |
| **Music / Rhythm (melos)** | Sound, song, and the rhythm of speech and action. |
| **Spectacle (opsis)** | Everything seen — set, costume, movement, visual effect. |

**Analogy.** The elements are like ingredients in a recipe: the same ingredients in different amounts and orders make very different dishes.

**Why it matters.** Analysing a performance means noticing how these elements work **together**, not in isolation.

**Common misconception.** *"The elements are separate boxes you can study one at a time and that''s enough."*
**Correction.** Their power comes from **combination** — a line of dialogue (language) delivered with a certain rhythm (music) while moving (spectacle) reveals character and advances plot all at once.

**Command-term questions.**
- *Identify* Aristotle''s six elements of drama.
- *Analyse* how two elements combine in a scene you have watched.

---','{"335":1,"concept":1,"the":15,"elements":8,"drama":3,"overview":1,"definition":1,"are":3,"building":1,"blocks":1,"every":1,"piece":1,"theatre":1,"combines":1,"grade":1,"focuses":1,"core":1,"three":1,"plot":3,"character":3,"theme":2,"and":9,"connects":1,"them":1,"classic":1,"aristotelian":1,"set":2,"aristotle":3,"six":2,"from":2,"poetics":1,"bce":1,"age":1,"appropriate":1,"awareness":1,"level":1,"element":1,"simple":1,"meaning":1,"mythos":1,"arrangement":1,"events":1,"story":2,"structure":1,"ethos":1,"people":1,"their":2,"qualities":1,"thought":1,"dianoia":1,"ideas":1,"meanings":1,"explored":1,"diction":1,"language":2,"lexis":1,"words":1,"spoken":1,"dialogue":2,"how":3,"expressed":1,"music":2,"rhythm":3,"melos":1,"sound":1,"song":1,"speech":1,"action":1,"spectacle":2,"opsis":1,"everything":1,"seen":1,"costume":1,"movement":1,"visual":1,"effect":1,"analogy":1,"like":1,"ingredients":2,"recipe":1,"same":1,"different":2,"amounts":1,"orders":1,"make":1,"very":1,"dishes":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"analysing":1,"performance":1,"means":1,"noticing":1,"these":1,"work":1,"together":1,"not":1,"isolation":1,"common":1,"misconception":1,"separate":1,"boxes":1,"you":2,"can":1,"study":1,"one":1,"time":1,"that":1,"enough":1,"correction":1,"power":1,"comes":1,"combination":1,"line":1,"delivered":1,"with":1,"certain":1,"while":1,"moving":1,"reveals":1,"advances":1,"all":1,"once":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"identify":1,"analyse":1,"two":1,"combine":1,"scene":1,"have":1,"watched":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_f2724b1d36e153a29a','file_14c714e4dfcb7d1697','theatre.md','Concept: Plot & Freytag''s Pyramid','**Definition.** **Plot** is the ordered sequence of events — what happens and in what order. A classic way to map a plot''s shape is **Freytag''s Pyramid** (Gustav Freytag, 1863), which describes a five-part dramatic structure.

| Stage | What happens | Example (a simple story) |
|-------|--------------|--------------------------|
| **1. Exposition** | Sets up characters, setting, and situation. | We meet the hero and their ordinary world. |
| **2. Rising action** | Conflict builds; complications and tension grow. | A problem appears and gets harder. |
| **3. Climax** | The turning point of highest tension. | The hero faces the decisive moment. |
| **4. Falling action** | Events unwind as consequences play out. | The results of the climax unfold. |
| **5. Resolution (dénouement)** | Conflict is settled; the story closes. | The situation reaches its new normal. |

**Analogy.** A plot is like a roller-coaster: the slow climb (rising action) to the top (climax), then the rush down (falling action) to the station (resolution).

**Real example.** In *Antigone*, the exposition establishes Antigone''s decision to bury her brother against the king''s law; rising action is her defiance and arrest; the climax is Creon''s fatal insistence; falling action and resolution bring the tragic consequences.

**Why it matters.** Structure controls tension and meaning — students use plot shape to build their own devised scenes (Criteria B and C).

**Common misconception.** *"Plot is the same as story / plot just means ''what it''s about.''"*
**Correction.** **Story** = the raw events; **plot** = how those events are **selected and arranged** for effect. Rearranging the order changes the plot even if the story is identical.

**Command-term questions.**
- *Identify* the five stages of Freytag''s pyramid.
- *Describe* the climax of a play or film you know.
- *Analyse* how the rising action builds tension in a chosen scene.

---','{"1863":1,"concept":1,"plot":9,"freytag":4,"pyramid":3,"definition":1,"the":25,"ordered":1,"sequence":1,"events":4,"what":4,"happens":2,"and":10,"order":2,"classic":1,"way":1,"map":1,"shape":2,"gustav":1,"which":1,"describes":1,"five":2,"part":1,"dramatic":1,"structure":2,"stage":1,"example":2,"simple":1,"story":5,"exposition":2,"sets":1,"characters":1,"setting":1,"situation":2,"meet":1,"hero":2,"their":2,"ordinary":1,"world":1,"rising":4,"action":7,"conflict":2,"builds":2,"complications":1,"tension":4,"grow":1,"problem":1,"appears":1,"gets":1,"harder":1,"climax":5,"turning":1,"point":1,"highest":1,"faces":1,"decisive":1,"moment":1,"falling":3,"unwind":1,"consequences":2,"play":2,"out":1,"results":1,"unfold":1,"resolution":3,"nouement":1,"settled":1,"closes":1,"reaches":1,"its":1,"new":1,"normal":1,"analogy":1,"like":1,"roller":1,"coaster":1,"slow":1,"climb":1,"top":1,"then":1,"rush":1,"down":1,"station":1,"real":1,"antigone":2,"establishes":1,"decision":1,"bury":1,"her":2,"brother":1,"against":1,"king":1,"law":1,"defiance":1,"arrest":1,"creon":1,"fatal":1,"insistence":1,"bring":1,"tragic":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"controls":1,"meaning":1,"students":1,"use":1,"build":1,"own":1,"devised":1,"scenes":1,"criteria":1,"common":1,"misconception":1,"same":1,"just":1,"means":1,"about":1,"correction":1,"raw":1,"how":2,"those":1,"are":1,"selected":1,"arranged":1,"for":1,"effect":1,"rearranging":1,"changes":1,"even":1,"identical":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"identify":1,"stages":1,"describe":1,"film":1,"you":1,"know":1,"analyse":1,"chosen":1,"scene":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_fc211ee9f4ae3cce50','file_14c714e4dfcb7d1697','theatre.md','Concept: Character (Protagonist & Antagonist)','**Definition.** A **character** is a fictional person in the drama, with motives, objectives, and traits. Two key roles:
- **Protagonist** — the main character the story follows (not always "the good guy").
- **Antagonist** — the character or force that **opposes** the protagonist and creates conflict.

**Real example.** In *Antigone*, **Antigone** is the protagonist and **Creon** (the king) is the antagonist. In *Oedipus Rex* (Sophocles), Oedipus is the protagonist opposed by fate and his own past.

**Analogy.** Protagonist and antagonist are like two magnets pushing against each other — their opposition is the engine that drives the plot forward.

**Why it matters.** Conflict between characters is the fuel of drama; understanding objectives helps actors make strong, believable choices (Criterion C).

**Common misconception.** *"The antagonist is always evil, and the protagonist is always the hero."*
**Correction.** The antagonist is simply the **opposing force** — sometimes sympathetic, sometimes society, nature, or fate. Protagonists can be flawed or even villainous.

**Command-term questions.**
- *Identify* the protagonist and antagonist in a chosen play.
- *Interpret* a character''s main objective (what they want) in a scene.
- *Analyse* how conflict between two characters develops the plot.

---','{"concept":1,"character":5,"protagonist":8,"antagonist":7,"definition":1,"fictional":1,"person":1,"the":20,"drama":2,"with":1,"motives":1,"objectives":2,"and":7,"traits":1,"two":3,"key":1,"roles":1,"main":2,"story":1,"follows":1,"not":1,"always":3,"good":1,"guy":1,"force":2,"that":2,"opposes":1,"creates":1,"conflict":3,"real":1,"example":1,"antigone":2,"creon":1,"king":1,"oedipus":2,"rex":1,"sophocles":1,"opposed":1,"fate":2,"his":1,"own":1,"past":1,"analogy":1,"are":1,"like":1,"magnets":1,"pushing":1,"against":1,"each":1,"other":1,"their":1,"opposition":1,"engine":1,"drives":1,"plot":2,"forward":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"between":2,"characters":2,"fuel":1,"understanding":1,"helps":1,"actors":1,"make":1,"strong":1,"believable":1,"choices":1,"criterion":1,"common":1,"misconception":1,"evil":1,"hero":1,"correction":1,"simply":1,"opposing":1,"sometimes":2,"sympathetic":1,"society":1,"nature":1,"protagonists":1,"can":1,"flawed":1,"even":1,"villainous":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"identify":1,"chosen":1,"play":1,"interpret":1,"objective":1,"what":1,"they":1,"want":1,"scene":1,"analyse":1,"how":1,"develops":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_b2f8251690a2087353','file_14c714e4dfcb7d1697','theatre.md','Concept: Theme','**Definition.** A **theme** is a central **idea, message, or question** a piece of theatre explores — e.g., justice, loyalty, power, fate, family, freedom.

**Real example.** *Antigone* explores the theme of **individual conscience vs. state law**; many comedies of Aristophanes explore the theme of politics and human folly.

**Analogy.** If plot is the "what happens," theme is the "so what?" — the idea left echoing after the story ends.

**Why it matters.** Theme gives a performance depth and helps an audience connect the story to their own lives.

**Common misconception.** *"The theme is just a one-word topic, like ''love.''"*
**Correction.** A topic is a word ("love"); a theme is a **statement or question** the play makes about it ("loyalty can demand painful sacrifice"). Theme is what the play *says* about the topic.

**Command-term questions.**
- *Identify* one theme in a play you have studied.
- *Describe* how the plot reveals that theme.
- *Interpret* the message the playwright may be sending.

---','{"concept":1,"theme":11,"definition":1,"central":1,"idea":2,"message":2,"question":2,"piece":1,"theatre":1,"explores":2,"justice":1,"loyalty":2,"power":1,"fate":1,"family":1,"freedom":1,"real":1,"example":1,"antigone":1,"the":14,"individual":1,"conscience":1,"state":1,"law":1,"many":1,"comedies":1,"aristophanes":1,"explore":1,"politics":1,"and":2,"human":1,"folly":1,"analogy":1,"plot":2,"what":3,"happens":1,"left":1,"echoing":1,"after":1,"story":2,"ends":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"gives":1,"performance":1,"depth":1,"helps":1,"audience":1,"connect":1,"their":1,"own":1,"lives":1,"common":1,"misconception":1,"just":1,"one":2,"word":2,"topic":3,"like":1,"love":2,"correction":1,"statement":1,"play":3,"makes":1,"about":2,"can":1,"demand":1,"painful":1,"sacrifice":1,"says":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"identify":1,"you":1,"have":1,"studied":1,"describe":1,"how":1,"reveals":1,"that":1,"interpret":1,"playwright":1,"may":1,"sending":1}'::jsonb);